body:
@WG-Security
It looks like this feature request is to prevent a function being created having the same name as a function exposed through a loaded signed module file.

PowerShell command precedence allows (proxy) functions and aliases to override module commands.  We recommend not changing this as it would be a significant breaking change.  In addition, users can already use module fully qualified command names to ensure they are running the command they expect, and this is encouraged as a best practice.

> Regardless if this is a security issue or not. This is still a reliability problem. If the script or module author cannot ensure the fully qualified cmdlet being called has the same behavior in dev as in production. This can and will cause unexpected behavior and the end user will blame the script or module author rather than the person who overloaded the cmdlets with a custom function or alias.

It should be exceedingly rare that someone would do this for a reason that is not explicitly for customization or mocking purposes. I don't think it's unreasonable for a module author to reply in this hypothetical that the scenario is not supported. Maybe someone would still be mad, but afaik this is all hypothetical and such a scenario has not occurred (*specifically* for a module qualified path, plenty of normal shadowing issues have occurred).

That said, even if we changed how command discovery of a module qualified invocation works, it could still be overridden by importing a module with the same name:

```powershell
New-Module -Name 'Microsoft.PowerShell.Utility' -ScriptBlock {
    function Add-Member {
    }

    Export-ModuleMember -Function Add-Member
} | Import-Module

Microsoft.PowerShell.Utility\Add-Member
```

They can even add a `$ExecutionContext.SessionState.InvokeCommand.PreCommandLookupAction` if they really want to. Or use modding tools like harmony to alter engine code at runtime. These things can be prevented with security tools, but from a module author perspective there has to be some acceptance that there are some scenarios you can't support or account for.
